Bucky did not live to see the new breed of modern, modular nuclear reactors. For example, Pebble Bed Modular Reactors (PBR) and Advanced Small Module Reactors (SMRs) would seem to (partly) address his concern about centralization and cost. 19/n

Bucky for example estimated that a wind tower built on top of every high voltage transmission tower in the US could generate 3.5X the countries total power output.But he was silent on the issue of baseload power and how a grid like this would be balanced and resilient. 18/n

He felt that large scale nuclear plants required vast sums of taxpayer money, and was co-opted by oil companies that wanted to maintain economic control of energy production.Bucky advocated for renewables - mainly hydro and wind, and radical improvements in efficiency. 17/n

Going back to our chart, nuclear is clocking in at a whopping 75 EROI. So Bucky loved #nuclear right?Actually he did not. But not for the reasons you might think.He did not like nuclear power due to the cost and centralization of control. 16/n
Note: The USA has a lot of natgas - 100 years worth give or take. This can provide plenty of transitional energy slaves to build the next phase of our energy infrastructure. 15/n

Which is why we have increasingly turned to Natural Gas in the US for baseload power. With an EROI of 28 it is almost equal to coal (30) in net energy but with only half the CO2 emissions. However, the EROI of NatGas will eventually fall as we exploit more of this resource. 14/n

Wind is more favorable for expansion - there are more potential sites than hydro. Permitting and licensing are still onerous, but not as much as dams.This is why US wind surpassed hydro in 2019. But of course, the wind does not always blow. 13/n https://t.co/nXUsTVxZMb

Looking back on the chart, Hydro looks great. It currently supplies 6% of electricity in the US. But it is impossible to meaningfully scale up. There are only so many rivers. Licensing, permitting, environmental are very costly and difficult for new hydro. 12/n

Our society is built on the energy slaves provided by fossil fuels. They are requiring more energy to extract. Once the EROI ratio falls below 7 we will still extract oil because we need it for plastics, fertilizer, etc.But energy slaves still need to come from somewhere. 11/n

So these EROI can vary quite a bit based on your assumptions, but to give a relative comparison:- Nuclear 75- Hydro 50- Wind 40- Coal 30- NatGas 28- Oil 10- Solar 4It's important to note solar is below the 7 EROI cutoff. Takes too many energy slaves to produce. 10/n

EROI is hard to calculate, you need to try to capture ALL of the lifecycle costs. For example, to calculate the EROI of nuclear, you need to estimate all of the energy slaves required to mine the uranium, process the concrete, smelt the iron, and build and operate the plant. 9/n

This ratio is called the net energy ratio, or "energy returned on energy invested" -> "EROEI".An EROEI of 7 is considered "breakeven" - produced enough surplus energy to sustain a complex socioeconomic system.US average EROI across all generating tech is 40.8/n

The early oil wells only required 1 energy slave to discover and extract 100 more. ratio = 100:1The 2010 Deepwater Horizon required going through 1500m of water and 4000m of earth crust. Far less efficient ratio of 10:1 energy slaves.Ratio will approach 1:1 with time. 7/n https://t.co/HvkJTDu1ZB

So coal, oil, natural gas is a "battery" of ancient sunshine that we have been utilizing as a source of surplus energy slaves for three centuries.The first oil well in the US was only 21 meters below ground. It did not take many energy slaves at all to exploit it. 6/n

The "solar income budget" is the amount of sunshine falling on the planet, which provides direct and indirect energy.This caps the "energy slaves" available for work.Fossil fuels allowed us to break the budget, but withdrawing from ancient sunlight stored in a "battery" 5/n

Travel illustrates the mastery of energy that enables our modern lifestyle. Humans have progressed from single person effort to harnessing "energy slaves" through a progression:- travel by own muscle power- by horse- by sail- by steambut all within "solar budget" 4/n

So Bucky coined the term "energy slave" & started to quantify how many energy slaves it takes to keep our modern society running.For example, filling up a gas tank with 16 gallons of gas is the equivalent of 4 energy slaves - the energy equivalent of 4 men working all year.3/n

Bucky thought the term "horsepower" was archaic, so invented a term more aligned with the human body.US and Swiss armies measured that a healthy soldier can do 2000 kilojoules of work in an 8-hour day.In 250 8-hour working days, that's 500 megajoules of work annually. 2/n https://t.co/r00ONpVJYV

12.The article also talks about solar pumps for agriculture without once mentioning that those are very different from grid electricity. No storage of electricity is required in pumps so they are much more cost efficient.
11.There is no doubt in my mind that the villagers would soon demand a grid connection. They should.
10.The problem arises from the fact that solar projects generate electricity in the day and the need for electricity is mostly at night. Hence, electricity needs to be stored and storage is costly.

9.Common TV time is strictly rationed. Of course the villagers want more. This is covered in just one paragraph at then end. Villagers want electricity that allows them a fridge. They would want heating and cooling like any of us.

8.That is not all. The electricity generated is strictly rationed. One fan, three lights and one charging point for each household. When 2 more households wanted to join in, they were give only 1 light.
7.Add to this the cost of replacement of battery and maintenance and solar does not look cheap even for this small village.

6.But there is a catch (of course). Only 15 of the 300 families benefit from the solar project. If all families need to benefit, then 20 such projects would be needed. Cost = 8.5 x 300 / 15 = Rs. 170 lakh

5.Maybe, it was very costly to connect the village to the grid and solar was much cheaper?Indeed, the state estimated that getting the grid to the village would cost Rs. 50 Lakh whereas the solar project only cost Rs. 8.5 Lakh!

4.Earlier people had to walk miles just to charge a mobile. They couldn‚Äôt work at night. Children couldn‚Äôt study. So what is the problem with the article?These are benefits of electricity and not solar electricity.

3.Article starts with how the lives of villagers has changed. This is the gratifying part. From being able to work/study at night, to watching TV, to charging a mobile, to sleeping under a fan. All benefits of electricity.
2.The story is about a small Hamlet in Tripura which did not have electricity. A solar power project was put up and 15 households got electricity.
